export const DEMO_SCRIPT = "## Opening â€” Inaugural Address\n\n[NOTE â€” 20 January 1961. Washington, D.C. Temperature: 22 Â°F / âˆ’6 Â°C. The crowd is vast. Speak slowly â€” your breath will be visible in the cold air.]\n\n[CLICK]\n\nVice President Johnson, Mr. Speaker, Mr. Chief Justice, President Eisenhower, Vice President Nixon, President Truman, reverend clergy, fellow citizens: [BREATHE]\n\n[PAUSE â€” let the formalities settle. Survey the crowd.]\n\nWe observe today not a victory of party [BREATHE] but a celebration of freedom â€” [BREATHE] symbolizing an end as well as a beginning â€” [BREATHE] signifying renewal as well as change.\n\n[PAUSE â€” let the opening land]\n\nFor I have sworn before you and Almighty God [BREATHE] the same solemn oath our forebears prescribed nearly a century and three-quarters ago.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nThe world is very different now. [BREATHE] For man holds in his mortal hands [SLOW] the power to abolish all forms of human poverty [BREATHE] and all forms of human life.\n\n[PAUSE â€” hold the weight of that contrast. 3â€“4 seconds.]\n\nAnd yet the same revolutionary beliefs for which our forebears fought [BREATHE] are still at issue around the globe â€” [BREATHE] the belief that the rights of man come not from the generosity of the state [BREATHE] but from the hand of God.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\n**We dare not forget today that we are the heirs of that first revolution.** [BREATHE]\n\n[PAUSE â€” let this declaration resonate]\n\nLet the word go forth from this time and place, [BREATHE] to friend and foe alike, [BREATHE] that the torch has been passed [SLOW] to a new generation of Americans â€” [BREATHE]\n\n[PAUSE â€” 3 seconds. This is one of the speech's defining images.]\n\nborn in this century, [BREATHE] tempered by war, [BREATHE] disciplined by a hard and bitter peace, [BREATHE] proud of our ancient heritage â€” [BREATHE] and unwilling to witness or permit [BREATHE] the slow undoing of those human rights to which this Nation has always been committed, [BREATHE] and to which we are committed today [BREATHE] at home and around the world.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nLet every nation know, [BREATHE] whether it wishes us well or ill, [BREATHE] that we shall pay any price, [BREATHE] bear any burden, [BREATHE] meet any hardship, [BREATHE] support any friend, [BREATHE] oppose any foe, [BREATHE] **in order to assure the survival and the success of liberty.**\n\n[PAUSE â€” 4 seconds. The cadence of that list should build and then land hard on the final clause.]\n\n---\n\n## Pledges to the World\n\n[CLICK]\n\n[NOTE â€” This section addresses allies and adversaries in turn. Keep the tone firm but generous â€” these are pledges, not threats.]\n\nTo those old allies whose cultural and spiritual origins we share, [BREATHE] we pledge the loyalty of faithful friends. [BREATHE] United, there is little we cannot do [BREATHE] in a host of cooperative ventures. [BREATHE] Divided, there is little we can do â€” [BREATHE] for we dare not meet a powerful challenge at odds and split asunder.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nTo those new States whom we welcome to the ranks of the free, [BREATHE] we pledge our word that one form of colonial control shall not have passed away [BREATHE] merely to be replaced by a far more iron tyranny.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nWe shall not always expect to find them supporting our view. [BREATHE] But we shall always hope to find them strongly supporting their own freedom â€” [BREATHE] and to remember that, in the past, [BREATHE] those who foolishly sought power by riding the back of the tiger [BREATHE] ended up inside.\n\n[PAUSE â€” let the metaphor land. Brief smile if appropriate.]\n\n[CLICK]\n\nTo those peoples in the huts and villages across half the globe [BREATHE] struggling to break the bonds of mass misery, [BREATHE] we pledge our best efforts to help them help themselves, [BREATHE] for whatever period is required â€” [BREATHE] not because the Communists may be doing it, [BREATHE] not because we seek their votes, [BREATHE] but because it is right.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\n**If a free society cannot help the many who are poor, [BREATHE] it cannot save the few who are rich.**\n\n[PAUSE â€” 3 seconds. This line often gets applause. Wait for it.]\n\n[CLICK]\n\nTo our sister republics south of our border, [BREATHE] we offer a special pledge â€” [BREATHE] to convert our good words into good deeds, [BREATHE] in a new alliance for progress, [BREATHE] to assist free men and free governments [BREATHE] in casting off the chains of poverty.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nBut this peaceful revolution of hope [BREATHE] cannot become the prey of hostile powers. [BREATHE] Let all our neighbors know [BREATHE] that we shall join with them to oppose aggression or subversion [BREATHE] anywhere in the Americas.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nAnd let every other power know [BREATHE] that this Hemisphere intends to remain the master of its own house.\n\n[PAUSE â€” firm. Brief.]\n\n---\n\n## To the United Nations and Our Adversaries\n\n[CLICK]\n\nTo that world assembly of sovereign states, the United Nations, [BREATHE] our last best hope in an age where the instruments of war [BREATHE] have far outpaced the instruments of peace, [BREATHE] we renew our pledge of support â€” [BREATHE]\n\nto prevent it from becoming merely a forum for invective â€” [BREATHE] to strengthen its shield of the new and the weak â€” [BREATHE] and to enlarge the area in which its writ may run.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\n[CLICK]\n\n[NOTE â€” The tone shifts here. You are addressing the Soviet Union directly. Measured, not hostile.]\n\nFinally, to those nations who would make themselves our adversary, [BREATHE] we offer not a pledge but a request: [BREATHE]\n\nthat both sides begin anew the quest for peace, [BREATHE] before the dark powers of destruction [BREATHE] unleashed by science [BREATHE] engulf all humanity in planned or accidental self-destruction.\n\n[PAUSE â€” 3 seconds]\n\nWe dare not tempt them with weakness. [BREATHE] For only when our arms are sufficient beyond doubt [BREATHE] can we be certain beyond doubt [BREATHE] that they will never be employed.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nBut neither can two great and powerful groups of nations [BREATHE] take comfort from our present course â€” [BREATHE] both sides overburdened by the cost of modern weapons, [BREATHE] both rightly alarmed by the steady spread of the deadly atom, [BREATHE] yet both racing to alter that uncertain balance of terror [BREATHE] that stays the hand of mankind's final war.\n\n[PAUSE â€” let the gravity build]\n\n---\n\n## A Call to Negotiate\n\n[CLICK]\n\n**So let us begin anew** â€” [BREATHE] [LOOK UP]\n\nremembering on both sides [BREATHE] that civility is not a sign of weakness, [BREATHE] and sincerity is always subject to proof.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nLet us never negotiate out of fear. [BREATHE] **But let us never fear to negotiate.**\n\n[PAUSE â€” 4 seconds. One of the most quoted lines. Let it breathe fully.]\n\nLet both sides explore what problems unite us [BREATHE] instead of belaboring those problems which divide us.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nLet both sides, for the first time, [BREATHE] formulate serious and precise proposals [BREATHE] for the inspection and control of arms â€” [BREATHE] and bring the absolute power to destroy other nations [BREATHE] under the absolute control of all nations.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nLet both sides seek to invoke [BREATHE] the wonders of science instead of its terrors. [BREATHE] Together let us explore the stars, [BREATHE] conquer the deserts, [BREATHE] eradicate disease, [BREATHE] tap the ocean depths, [BREATHE] and encourage the arts and commerce.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\n[CLICK]\n\nLet both sides unite [BREATHE] to heed in all corners of the earth [BREATHE] the command of Isaiah â€” [SLOW] to \"undo the heavy burdens [BREATHE] and to let the oppressed go free.\"\n\n[PAUSE â€” 3 seconds]\n\nAnd if a beachhead of cooperation [BREATHE] may push back the jungle of suspicion, [BREATHE] let both sides join in creating [BREATHE] a new endeavor â€” [BREATHE] not a new balance of power, [BREATHE] but a new world of law, [BREATHE] where the strong are just [BREATHE] and the weak secure [BREATHE] and the peace preserved.\n\n[PAUSE â€” hold. This is the vision statement.]\n\n---\n\n## The Call to Service\n\n[CLICK]\n\n[NOTE â€” The speech pivots inward here. You are now addressing the American people directly. Warm but serious.]\n\nAll this will not be finished in the first one hundred days. [BREATHE] Nor will it be finished in the first one thousand days, [BREATHE] nor in the life of this Administration, [BREATHE] nor even perhaps in our lifetime on this planet. [BREATHE]\n\n**But let us begin.**\n\n[PAUSE â€” 3 seconds. Simple and powerful.]\n\n[LOOK UP]\n\nIn your hands, my fellow citizens, [BREATHE] more than in mine, [BREATHE] will rest the final success or failure of our course. [BREATHE]\n\nSince this country was founded, [BREATHE] each generation of Americans has been summoned [BREATHE] to give testimony to its national loyalty. [BREATHE]\n\nThe graves of young Americans who answered the call to service [BREATHE] surround the globe.\n\n[PAUSE â€” respect the fallen. 3 seconds of silence.]\n\nNow the trumpet summons us again â€” [BREATHE] not as a call to bear arms, [BREATHE] though arms we need; [BREATHE] not as a call to battle, [BREATHE] though embattled we are â€” [BREATHE] but a call to bear the burden of a long twilight struggle, [BREATHE] year in and year out, [BREATHE] \"rejoicing in hope, patient in tribulation\" â€” [BREATHE]\n\na struggle against the common enemies of man: [BREATHE] tyranny, [BREATHE] poverty, [BREATHE] disease, [BREATHE] and war itself.\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nCan we forge against these enemies [BREATHE] a grand and global alliance, [BREATHE] North and South, [BREATHE] East and West, [BREATHE] that can assure a more fruitful life for all mankind? [BREATHE]\n\n**Will you join in that historic effort?**\n\n[PAUSE â€” 3 seconds. Look directly at the crowd.] [LOOK UP]\n\n---\n\n## Ask Not â€” The Closing\n\n[CLICK]\n\n[NOTE â€” This is the climax. Everything before has built to this moment. Slow right down. Every word lands.]\n\nIn the long history of the world, [BREATHE] only a few generations have been granted the role [BREATHE] of defending freedom in its hour of maximum danger. [BREATHE]\n\nI do not shrink from this responsibility â€” [BREATHE] **I welcome it.** [BREATHE]\n\n[PAUSE]\n\nI do not believe that any of us [BREATHE] would exchange places with any other people [BREATHE] or any other generation. [BREATHE]\n\nThe energy, the faith, the devotion [BREATHE] which we bring to this endeavor [BREATHE] will light our country [BREATHE] and all who serve it â€” [BREATHE]\n\nand the glow from that fire [BREATHE] can truly light the world. [SLOW]\n\n[PAUSE â€” 4 seconds. Let the image settle.]\n\n[CLICK]\n\nAnd so, my fellow Americans: [PAUSE] [LOOK UP]\n\n**Ask not what your country can do for you** [BREATHE] [SLOW]\n\n**ask what you can do for your country.**\n\n[PAUSE â€” the longest pause in the speech. 5â€“6 seconds. Look up. Hold the silence. Let the crowd respond.]\n\nMy fellow citizens of the world: [BREATHE] [LOOK UP]\n\nask not what America will do for you, [BREATHE] but what together [BREATHE] we can do [BREATHE] for the freedom of man.\n\n[PAUSE â€” 4 seconds]\n\n[CLICK]\n\n[NOTE â€” The benediction. Slower still. This is the farewell.]\n\nFinally, whether you are citizens of America [BREATHE] or citizens of the world, [BREATHE] ask of us the same high standards of strength and sacrifice [BREATHE] which we ask of you. [BREATHE]\n\nWith a good conscience our only sure reward, [BREATHE] with history the final judge of our deeds, [BREATHE] let us go forth to lead the land we love, [BREATHE] [SLOW]\n\nasking His blessing and His help, [BREATHE] but knowing that here on earth [BREATHE] **God's work must truly be our own.**\n\n[PAUSE â€” end. Hold the silence for a full 5 seconds before stepping back.] [SMILE]\n";
